published in 2014, if you were to have an ecDNA interest

29
00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:42.720
group,

30
00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:45.800
it would be about three people in the room.

31
00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:50.300
And now it's become one of the most important topics in the field of cancer,

32
00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:54.020
and that's really because of you. There's a culture to this

33
00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.940
ecDNA field that's allowing it to move rapidly.

34
00:01:57.300 --> 00:02:01.120
It's a highly inclusive, highly collaborative culture where we

35
00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:05.160
encourage and want people to come into the field to lower the barriers for

36
00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:09.200
entry to research. And the only requirement is to pay

37
00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:11.750
it forward, to share your data as you move forward.

38
00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:15.980
So please keep that in mind. We are here, we are open, and we're looking

39
00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:18.940
forward to having new collaborators in the field.

40
00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:22.920
So without further ado, I'm going to launch into my talk.

41
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:27.880
So

42
00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:32.080
when we think about genes and how they're inherited,

43
00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:33.859
we think about these,

44
00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:35.520
chromosomes.

45
00:02:37.640 --> 00:02:37.820
So

46
00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:39.880
they're the physical unit

47
00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:42.800
of genetic information inheritance.

48
00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:47.240
They're how information is passed from parents to children or from cell to

49
00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:48.760
cell during division.

50
00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:53.180
Everything we know about human genetics stems from our

51
00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.540
understanding of chromosomes. They set the

52
00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:00.430
rules from how cancers form to how cancers evolve.

53
00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:04.430
And in fact, when we think about precision oncology, they're the basis of

54
00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:06.220
it. With the mapping of the human genome

55
00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:11.080
and the availability of next generation sequencing, we can

56
00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:14.720
map these lesions and identify what's gone wrong with each individual

57
00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:18.120
patient's cancer and tailor therapies for it.

58
00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:21.990
However, the problem is that the effectiveness is

59
00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.740
very incomplete. For many patients, these methods haven't

60
00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:29.700
helped patients. And part of the reason is what isn't

61
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:33.660
in this picture, and that's these extrachromosomal

62
00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:37.680
DNA particles that have been hiding in the nucleus in plain sight.

63
00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:42.380
This morning, I'm going to tell you about a historical context to this

64
00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:46.240
field, where the field is going, share some biological

65
00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:49.760
research and its implications, and foreshadow the

66
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.010
future before I turn it over to my colleagues.

67
00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:56.400
So this work really started back in about

68
00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:00.460
2013, and it started with a graduate student in my lab named David

69
00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:02.580
Nathanson, who's now a professor at UCLA.

70
00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.080
And we were struck by something. We were studying glioblastoma that

71
00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:10.580
has a very high frequency of EGF receptor amplifications.

72
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.970
It should have been the poster child for EGF receptor targeted therapy, and

73
00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:17.360
yet it wasn't. The patients didn't respond.

74
00:04:17.959 --> 00:04:21.140
And there were lots of reasons that were given, and one of them was this massive

75
00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:24.500
amount of heterogeneity, how one cell could vary from another.

76
00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:28.140
Going all the way back to 1976, Peter Nowell had put forward this

77
00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:32.100
clonal evolution hypothesis that cells may differ

78
00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:36.060
in their DNA and that when you treat, you are going to

79
00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:39.680
select for the cells that are most resistant, and it should change over time, and

80
00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:41.680
if you were to remove the drug, it should change back.

81
00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:46.040
And we deployed single-cell technologies to look at this, and in fact, the

82
00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:47.260
tumors changed,

83
00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.900
but they didn't do it at the rate that we expected.

84
00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:54.840
It was lightning fast, and that made no sense by classical

85
00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:58.290
genetics. Even more strangely, look at this

86
00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:01.980
schematic for a moment. Let's just say red here means you have a lot of the EGF

87
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.580
receptor oncogene amplified, and yellow means you have very little.

88
00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:10.380
If you were to take a yellow cell and put it into a dish or a mouse, you'd

89
00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:13.860
expect to get a, quote, "yellow tumor," or one with low EGF receptor

90
00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:17.740
amplification. If you took a red, you should get a red tumor with

91
00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:20.520
high amplification, but that's not what happened.

92
00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:24.540
Every single cell gave rise to the same original tumor

93
00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:28.680
with this full spectrum heterogeneity, and there was simply no way to explain that

94
00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:32.880
by classical genetics. So we basically

95
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.700
looked because we realized you can't actually tell where a piece of DNA is

96
00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:39.540
inside the nucleus of a cancer cell during interphase.

97
00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:43.260
The only time you can tell is when the chromosomes line up.

98
00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:46.020
And that's what we did here, and it was quite illuminating.

99
00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:50.000
The blue here, this is a glioblastoma sample from a patient, and the blue

100
00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.480
are the chromosomes stained with DAPI.

101
00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:56.960
The red is the EGF receptor oncogene, and the green is the chromosome 7

102
00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:59.510
centromere probe. It's supposed to be on chromosome 7.

103
00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:02.830
You're supposed to have two copies. Here you have close to 100.

104
00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:06.056
And noticeThat almost none of it is on chromosomes.

105
00:06:06.396 --> 00:06:10.136
And then you treat with an EGF receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitor, and the DNA

106
00:06:10.196 --> 00:06:13.936
almost completely disappears. And then you remove the drug, and it very

107
00:06:13.976 --> 00:06:17.076
quickly reappears. Now, that statement should shock you.

108
00:06:17.636 --> 00:06:20.976
You're treating with a tyrosine kinase inhibitor, and the DNA is almost

109
00:06:20.996 --> 00:06:23.816
disappearing, and you remove the drug, and it's reappearing.

110
00:06:24.096 --> 00:06:28.076
We published in "Science" in 2014 to essentially

111
00:06:28.136 --> 00:06:29.796
a colossal scratching of heads.

112
00:06:31.276 --> 00:06:34.246
And I remember talking with people about it, and they would say,

113
00:06:35.456 --> 00:06:38.816
"The oncogene I study, c-Myc, it's on chromosome eight,"

114
00:06:39.556 --> 00:06:43.376
and I'd say, "When it's amplified." And say, "How do you know?" And they'd pull out

115
00:06:43.436 --> 00:06:47.316
a TCGA map. And I remember thinking of Ptolemy's map of the solar

116
00:06:47.416 --> 00:06:51.116
system. Maybe the sequencing measurements were absolutely right, but the

117
00:06:51.176 --> 00:06:54.416
map was wrong. And so at that point, I started working with

118
00:06:56.076 --> 00:06:57.865
Vineet Vafna, who's speaking after me,

119
00:06:59.456 --> 00:07:02.116
because Vineet also had the same suspicion.

120
00:07:02.136 --> 00:07:05.656
And what we did in a paper that was spearheaded by Kristin Turner at the time, a

121
00:07:05.736 --> 00:07:09.696
postdoc in the lab, was to ask, where are genes actually amplified?

122
00:07:09.736 --> 00:07:13.636
And we did it by integrating sequencing and the technology that allows

123
00:07:13.676 --> 00:07:16.516
us to ask does this amplification arise as a circle

124
00:07:17.676 --> 00:07:21.636
and looking during metaphases. And the results were crystal clear,

125
00:07:21.756 --> 00:07:25.436
as you can see in these pictures. All of these driver oncogenes, when they're

126
00:07:25.516 --> 00:07:29.196
amplified, are frequently amplified on extrachromosomal DNA

127
00:07:29.236 --> 00:07:33.176
particles. So we published that, and people began to pay attention.

128
00:07:34.636 --> 00:07:37.656
And have a look at these scanning electron micrographs.

129
00:07:37.956 --> 00:07:41.376
There they are in front of your eyes, bagels, donuts, SpaghettiOs,

130
00:07:41.896 --> 00:07:45.536
whatever you want to call them. These circular DNA particles that have been hiding

131
00:07:45.616 --> 00:07:48.416
in plain sight in the nucleus of cancer cells.

132
00:07:48.956 --> 00:07:51.116
And since then, we've learned a lot about them.

133
00:07:51.496 --> 00:07:54.596
We've learned that they're large, frequently between a million and five million

134
00:07:54.676 --> 00:07:55.296
base pairs.

135
00:07:56.176 --> 00:07:59.056
We know that they're chromatinized, that is, they're wound around these

136
00:07:59.096 --> 00:08:02.916
nucleosomes' histone cores but not exactly in the

137
00:08:02.936 --> 00:08:06.736
same way as normal chromosomal DNA. It's much more accessible.

138
00:08:07.356 --> 00:08:09.976
The chromatin is like an accordion.

139
00:08:10.036 --> 00:08:13.776
It opens and closes to allow or exclude the transcriptional

140
00:08:13.816 --> 00:08:17.536
machinery. On ecDNA, it's always open and accessible and

141
00:08:17.616 --> 00:08:21.576
transcribing. We've learned that they are not found in normal

142
00:08:21.636 --> 00:08:25.456
tissues and that they occur through at least two

143
00:08:25.496 --> 00:08:28.696
mechanisms, through the double-strand breaks and through

144
00:08:28.736 --> 00:08:30.956
chromothripsis, which I'll mention both.

145
00:08:31.796 --> 00:08:35.716
So one of the questions that came up is, why did you see this when

146
00:08:35.817 --> 00:08:39.636
other people hadn't? And the answer is actually other people had.

147
00:08:40.557 --> 00:08:44.506
And I'll talk about that, but there was more to the story than that, and it

148
00:08:44.576 --> 00:08:48.196
had to do with how we look. In the old days, cancer biologists

149
00:08:48.236 --> 00:08:51.636
would interrogate cancer cells by looking at tumor cells under a

150
00:08:51.656 --> 00:08:54.976
microscope. And what they had then was fantastic spatial

151
00:08:55.016 --> 00:08:58.726
resolution when they would make metaphases of tumor cells, but very

152
00:08:58.796 --> 00:09:01.376
little genome resolution, and the technology's changed.

153
00:09:01.726 --> 00:09:05.456
They moved from fish probes to microarrays, and then

154
00:09:05.496 --> 00:09:08.986
there's the mapping of the human genome and next-generation sequencing

155
00:09:09.036 --> 00:09:09.836
technologies.

156
00:09:10.996 --> 00:09:14.896
But you realize when we're doing that, we have fantastic genome

157
00:09:14.956 --> 00:09:18.946
resolution now, but the spatial resolution is an inference because what we're

158
00:09:18.976 --> 00:09:22.696
doing is we're mapping short reads back to the reference genome,

159
00:09:23.156 --> 00:09:26.136
but the reference genome comes from normal cells, and there's an implicit

160
00:09:26.196 --> 00:09:29.956
assumption that things are in cancer cells where they are in normal cells, and

161
00:09:30.016 --> 00:09:32.216
that actually hadn't been interrogated.

162
00:09:37.516 --> 00:09:38.876
Trying to go forward here.

163
00:09:40.756 --> 00:09:41.216
Let's try.

164
00:09:44.816 --> 00:09:48.796
So you might say all that matters is the amount

165
00:09:48.916 --> 00:09:51.836
of the DNA because it's DNA to RNA and protein.

166
00:09:52.716 --> 00:09:55.776
But that's actually not true, and this picture explains why.

167
00:09:59.436 --> 00:10:03.336
Metazoans, multicellular organisms, developed chromosomes so that during a cell

168
00:10:03.376 --> 00:10:05.776
division, each daughter cell gets the same DNA.

169
00:10:07.056 --> 00:10:09.196
So let's just say you had three copies.

170
00:10:09.216 --> 00:10:10.836
When the cell is getting ready to divide,

171
00:10:11.756 --> 00:10:15.556
it would make six copies, and each chromosome would be sent to daughter

172
00:10:15.656 --> 00:10:18.116
cells so that it would be parceled three and three.

173
00:10:18.516 --> 00:10:22.416
But these extrachromosomal DNA particles lack centromeres, and as a consequence,

174
00:10:22.736 --> 00:10:26.696
the three become six, but they can be parceled six and zero or five

175
00:10:26.716 --> 00:10:29.316
and one or four and two or three and three.

176
00:10:29.336 --> 00:10:32.966
Notice two things just happened. One, you've doubled the potential

177
00:10:32.976 --> 00:10:36.036
copy number. I always wondered, how do you get 30, 40, 50,

178
00:10:36.376 --> 00:10:40.336
60, 70 copies? The second thing you've done is you've increased the

179
00:10:40.356 --> 00:10:43.836
variance, which is what Darwin taught us is the fuel for

180
00:10:43.876 --> 00:10:44.476
evolution.

181
00:10:45.736 --> 00:10:49.656
So what this allows and what this does is instead of every cell division creating

182
00:10:49.696 --> 00:10:53.416
an equal set, every cell division actually creates a

183
00:10:53.456 --> 00:10:55.816
bell-shaped curve, and it keeps going.

184
00:10:56.296 --> 00:11:00.216
And that creates this enormous variation and the ability to be

185
00:11:00.336 --> 00:11:03.716
selected for under various conditions incredibly quickly.

186
00:11:04.086 --> 00:11:06.036
And this has profound implications.

187
00:11:06.576 --> 00:11:08.216
Permit a speculation for a moment.

188
00:11:08.556 --> 00:11:11.356
Bacteria have circular genomes and plasmids.

189
00:11:11.996 --> 00:11:13.736
Every single cell is a unique organism.

190
00:11:13.866 --> 00:11:17.276
Daughter cells don't have to have the same DNA as mother cells, and the species

191
00:11:17.336 --> 00:11:20.916
evolves very quickly. That's why we struggle with antibiotic resistance.

192
00:11:22.156 --> 00:11:25.776
Plants and animals developed chromosomes so that each daughter cell gets the

193
00:11:25.876 --> 00:11:29.796
same DNA during a cell division. It's as if cancer pulled

194
00:11:29.836 --> 00:11:33.666
an ancient trick by grafting these circular DNA structures

195
00:11:34.176 --> 00:11:35.736
onto the chromosomal backbone.

196
00:11:37.356 --> 00:11:38.276
So at this point,

197
00:11:39.216 --> 00:11:42.516
I connected with Howard Chang. I gave a talk at Stanford in

198
00:11:42.656 --> 00:11:45.996
2017, and Howard, working with Will Greenleaf, had just developed this

199
00:11:46.056 --> 00:11:49.636
ATAC-seq technology to look at chromatin accessibility.

200
00:11:49.956 --> 00:11:53.716
And he just published a paper on how chromatin accessibility

201
00:11:53.756 --> 00:11:55.776
signatures are very informative in cancer.

202
00:11:56.136 --> 00:11:59.176
And Howard came to me after my talk and said, "Paul, I think I'm seeing

203
00:11:59.256 --> 00:12:02.516
accessibility signatures that come from the

204
00:12:02.556 --> 00:12:06.296
extrachromosomal DNA particles that you described." And that started a working

205
00:12:06.316 --> 00:12:09.646
relationship that continues through today and the work that I'm going to talk

206
00:12:09.736 --> 00:12:10.316
about.

207
00:12:11.336 --> 00:12:14.716
It also is critically done in very close collaboration with Howard.

208
00:12:15.016 --> 00:12:18.856
We also began a Cancer Grand Challenges award, for which we're incredibly

209
00:12:18.916 --> 00:12:22.236
grateful because it allowed us to work in a completely different way.

210
00:12:22.376 --> 00:12:24.216
Talk about global and partnership.

211
00:12:24.636 --> 00:12:26.836
This has allowed us to work in a very different way.

212
00:12:26.896 --> 00:12:30.876
The schematic on the right shows how by using this, we

213
00:12:30.916 --> 00:12:34.664
can-Take and combine technologies to

214
00:12:34.684 --> 00:12:37.884
interrogate the biology in samples,

215
00:12:38.904 --> 00:12:42.764
experimental models, and in clinical samples from patients, so that we

216
00:12:42.784 --> 00:12:46.684
continue to learn from patients and we develop computational tools as a

217
00:12:46.744 --> 00:12:50.684
framework that we try to export and share with the broader community.

218
00:12:52.324 --> 00:12:56.124
What we've learned to date is that there are at least two ways that

219
00:12:56.144 --> 00:12:59.834
extrachromosomal DNA can form. We've learned that paired double-strand breaks,

220
00:12:59.904 --> 00:13:03.084
particularly in the context of tumor cells that have lost a tumor suppressor like

221
00:13:03.124 --> 00:13:07.004
P53, creates these circular DNA

222
00:13:07.084 --> 00:13:10.744
particles. There's nothing that's going to prevent the ligation of

223
00:13:10.804 --> 00:13:12.324
these ends. But

224
00:13:13.404 --> 00:13:17.024
you have to have lost a suppressor, and on top of that,

225
00:13:17.384 --> 00:13:21.313
you have to have a gene that encodes a gain of function.

226
00:13:21.624 --> 00:13:25.604
The genome is huge, so these events could be happening, but it's only when you pick

227
00:13:25.644 --> 00:13:29.534
up a Myc or an EGF receptor in the context of a suppressor loss, that

228
00:13:29.564 --> 00:13:32.604
the then non-Mendelian inheritance goes off to the races.

229
00:13:32.974 --> 00:13:36.804
Another mechanism that's been described by many, including Peter Lee, Don

230
00:13:36.883 --> 00:13:40.364
Cleveland, Peter Campbell, David Pelman, and others, is

231
00:13:40.404 --> 00:13:44.124
chromothripsis. That is when a chromosome lags and it goes into a

232
00:13:44.144 --> 00:13:47.624
micronucleus. It can get chopped to bits and the particles reassemble

233
00:13:48.024 --> 00:13:51.684
into extrachromosomal DNA using very much the same sorts of rules.

234
00:13:53.084 --> 00:13:57.064
So one of the most important things we did was we brought in Andrea Ventura, who

235
00:13:57.104 --> 00:14:00.964
does mouse genetic modeling. And Andrea Ventura used the Cre-Lox

236
00:14:01.004 --> 00:14:04.944
system. In Cre-Lox, you typically put what you want to get rid

237
00:14:05.064 --> 00:14:07.784
of into the garbage can. That's actually a circle.

238
00:14:08.104 --> 00:14:11.944
So what Andrea wisely did was, what if you put what you wanted

239
00:14:12.004 --> 00:14:15.944
into that circle? And that actually he's used to model extrachromosomal

240
00:14:15.964 --> 00:14:18.804
DNA in a very programmable fashion.

241
00:14:18.824 --> 00:14:22.004
And what's important about Andrea's work is that it actually

242
00:14:22.014 --> 00:14:25.714
shows that ecDNA is transformative in these

243
00:14:25.744 --> 00:14:28.004
very tightly controlled mouse genetic models.

244
00:14:29.564 --> 00:14:32.064
So then we start thinking more about this issue of inheritance.

245
00:14:32.144 --> 00:14:35.984
Everybody knows this picture, Darwin's branching tree of life,

246
00:14:36.504 --> 00:14:40.264
that was describing evolution, but then became very

247
00:14:40.304 --> 00:14:42.524
critical for thinking about cancer evolution.

248
00:14:42.753 --> 00:14:46.724
And the idea is you take pieces of the DNA and you sequence, and you can say,

249
00:14:46.784 --> 00:14:50.704
"I see the mutation here, but not here, but not here, but there." And you use

250
00:14:50.744 --> 00:14:54.344
that to infer whether a mutation is clonal or

251
00:14:54.944 --> 00:14:57.984
truncal, or whether it's in a branch.

252
00:14:59.084 --> 00:15:03.064
But that assumes chromosomes, because Darwin

253
00:15:03.104 --> 00:15:07.054
was studying finches. If Darwin had made this

254
00:15:07.084 --> 00:15:10.344
picture from bacteria, it would look very different.

255
00:15:10.404 --> 00:15:13.964
And realizing this and this concept of random

256
00:15:14.004 --> 00:15:17.824
inheritance, essentially that the heredity by descent actually becomes

257
00:15:17.864 --> 00:15:20.844
random, this has profound implications

258
00:15:20.864 --> 00:15:24.444
because that means that cancer can follow

259
00:15:24.464 --> 00:15:28.164
non-Mendelian inheritance when it's driven by extrachromosomal

260
00:15:28.224 --> 00:15:31.524
DNA. And we've found this again and again.

261
00:15:31.664 --> 00:15:34.124
You can really predict how this actually works.

262
00:15:34.454 --> 00:15:38.284
So the extrachromosomal DNA has profound implications for

263
00:15:38.324 --> 00:15:41.804
what cancers do by how these cancer-causing genes are

264
00:15:41.844 --> 00:15:43.084
inherited.

265
00:15:44.284 --> 00:15:47.604
And this has important implications for thinking about drug

266
00:15:47.664 --> 00:15:51.464
resistance. You can imagine this is a process that continues.

267
00:15:52.044 --> 00:15:55.844
Everything from oncogene switching to the development of, quote,

268
00:15:56.124 --> 00:15:59.784
"new oncogenes" that drive that switch to resistance to targeted

269
00:15:59.844 --> 00:16:03.424
therapies, all of these, it has been demonstrated that

270
00:16:03.464 --> 00:16:04.444
extrachromosomal

271
00:16:05.244 --> 00:16:07.204
DNA can actually drive these features.

272
00:16:07.884 --> 00:16:10.684
It also can drive immunosuppression.

273
00:16:10.884 --> 00:16:14.604
We brought James Chen in on our team, who's been doing brilliant

274
00:16:14.684 --> 00:16:17.144
work. There's a paper by Tole et al.

275
00:16:17.224 --> 00:16:20.924
that's in bioRxiv that shows that ecDNA suppresses the

276
00:16:20.984 --> 00:16:24.724
cGAS-STING system. So this has profound

277
00:16:24.804 --> 00:16:27.544
implications for cancer drug resistance.

278
00:16:29.244 --> 00:16:32.704
EcDNA also changes what the genes

279
00:16:32.824 --> 00:16:36.504
actually do. And then this was a schematic that was put forward by Shaowei

280
00:16:36.644 --> 00:16:40.384
Yan, a graduate student at Howard's lab, a postdoc in Howard's lab, whom I

281
00:16:40.444 --> 00:16:41.004
co-mentor,

282
00:16:42.004 --> 00:16:45.884
and who's now in my lab. And she's pointed out here some very important

283
00:16:45.984 --> 00:16:47.684
features of ecDNA. First of all,

284
00:16:48.664 --> 00:16:52.304
the presence on these circular ecDNA particles changes how the

285
00:16:52.404 --> 00:16:54.664
genes are expressed or regulated in cis.

286
00:16:54.904 --> 00:16:58.424
So when we think about gene regulation, we think about loops in which enhancers

287
00:16:58.464 --> 00:17:01.344
become proximal to promoters to drive gene expression.

288
00:17:01.404 --> 00:17:05.164
So you think about a string with a bunch of loops and things that are far apart

289
00:17:05.184 --> 00:17:09.124
from each other or too far apart to interact, and you have insulator units in

290
00:17:09.164 --> 00:17:13.024
between. Imagine taking that string and turning it

291
00:17:13.045 --> 00:17:16.904
into a loop. Now everything is close, and the insulators don't

292
00:17:17.004 --> 00:17:20.864
matter. It goes even beyond that. There's new forms of regulation

293
00:17:20.884 --> 00:17:24.305
in trans, as circles interact with each other in something called

294
00:17:24.664 --> 00:17:28.325
ecDNA hubs, that was described by King Hung in

295
00:17:28.444 --> 00:17:32.354
Howard's lab. And these hubs allow you to have interactions between enhancers and

296
00:17:32.444 --> 00:17:36.264
promoters across circles, sometimes even bearing different

297
00:17:36.304 --> 00:17:39.684
oncogenes, sharing transcriptional machinery to dramatically

298
00:17:39.744 --> 00:17:43.534
increase the output. When you take those features and you add them

299
00:17:43.604 --> 00:17:47.094
onto this powerful non-Mendelian inheritance, you have a

300
00:17:47.124 --> 00:17:49.124
recipe for genomic chaos.

301
00:17:50.724 --> 00:17:53.684
So this is what these hubs actually look like.

302
00:17:54.364 --> 00:17:57.764
You can see them visually, and you can actually do

303
00:17:57.804 --> 00:18:01.424
experiments that show that these are actually functional units that are

304
00:18:01.444 --> 00:18:03.784
dramatically increasing transcription.

305
00:18:04.224 --> 00:18:07.504
So I've actually just set up for you a paradox.

306
00:18:08.184 --> 00:18:11.784
Said that ecDNA is randomly inherited and also said that

307
00:18:11.824 --> 00:18:15.704
ecDNA particles can interact with each other in trans in a favorable

308
00:18:15.764 --> 00:18:19.554
fashion. So you would predict that they'd want to keep those particles

309
00:18:19.584 --> 00:18:22.344
together. But how would that actually work?

310
00:18:22.944 --> 00:18:26.304
Well, we looked at it in a paper that was spearheaded by King Hung, Matt Jones from

311
00:18:26.364 --> 00:18:30.124
Howard's lab, and Ivy Wang and EJ Curtis, EJ's right here in the third

312
00:18:30.184 --> 00:18:30.364
row,

313
00:18:31.224 --> 00:18:32.464
from my lab,

314
00:18:33.444 --> 00:18:37.412
to actually ask the questionIs this happening and how does it

315
00:18:37.452 --> 00:18:39.952
work? And the answer is they are co-inherited.

316
00:18:40.532 --> 00:18:43.861
And the real question is how? And I think the breakthrough came from Ivy Wang, a

317
00:18:43.932 --> 00:18:47.052
post-doc in my lab. Normally, genes are supposed to stop

318
00:18:47.092 --> 00:18:50.692
transcribing during mitosis. But when they're on extra

319
00:18:50.712 --> 00:18:54.232
chromosomal DNA, as you can see here, this is nascent RNA fish

320
00:18:54.572 --> 00:18:55.892
looking at the MYC transcript.

321
00:18:57.032 --> 00:19:00.592
The ecDNA is when it's on the circles, it can reintegrate back into

322
00:19:00.632 --> 00:19:04.272
chromosomes. That's the HSR. And you can see same gene on a

323
00:19:04.332 --> 00:19:08.192
circle transcribes during mitosis, but stops transcribing when it

324
00:19:08.232 --> 00:19:12.202
goes back onto chromosomes. And that becomes critical because in fact, working

325
00:19:12.212 --> 00:19:15.532
with Ben Cravatt, we were able to show that if you blocked transcription

326
00:19:15.612 --> 00:19:19.292
initiation, you blocked the co-inheritance of these particles.

327
00:19:21.092 --> 00:19:24.632
Another area of genomic chaos is some recent work that was spearheaded by

328
00:19:24.692 --> 00:19:25.832
Hyerim Yee

329
00:19:26.792 --> 00:19:29.812
and Shuzhang, co-mentored by Howard Chang and myself.

330
00:19:30.912 --> 00:19:34.512
I always wondered, where do amplified fusion oncogenes come from?

331
00:19:34.912 --> 00:19:38.392
And there's so much structural variation that you might think about arising from

332
00:19:38.472 --> 00:19:40.952
ecDNA. Could that be a potent source?

333
00:19:41.432 --> 00:19:42.882
So by integrating

334
00:19:43.912 --> 00:19:47.692
sequencing and this tool called Amplicon Architect that Vineet Bafna developed and

335
00:19:47.712 --> 00:19:51.622
will tell you about, we looked at the genome structure and the transcriptional

336
00:19:51.692 --> 00:19:55.192
output in human cancers of many, many different types.

337
00:19:55.502 --> 00:19:59.372
And it turns out that ecDNA is a factory for structural

338
00:19:59.432 --> 00:20:02.952
variation and for creating genomic

339
00:20:03.112 --> 00:20:05.932
fusions that actually result in transcript

340
00:20:06.052 --> 00:20:09.192
fusions. And that in fact, they

341
00:20:09.252 --> 00:20:12.232
are all over many different parts of the body.

342
00:20:12.352 --> 00:20:14.682
We focused on the PVT1-MYC fusion

343
00:20:15.672 --> 00:20:18.232
and identified the gain-of-function mechanisms by

344
00:20:19.112 --> 00:20:22.632
which this fusion has enhanced activity relative to the wild type

345
00:20:22.692 --> 00:20:26.552
transcript, but we also see it in different cancer types as depicted

346
00:20:26.632 --> 00:20:30.392
here. That's a completely open landscape, and Hyerim Yee is giving a talk

347
00:20:30.432 --> 00:20:33.172
about this here at the meeting, which I would encourage you to go

348
00:20:33.212 --> 00:20:36.702
to. So then this raises yet another interesting

349
00:20:36.792 --> 00:20:40.692
question. If they don't have centromeres, how do they get to daughter cells

350
00:20:40.792 --> 00:20:43.412
during a cell division? Well, there's a trick here.

351
00:20:43.872 --> 00:20:47.212
Episomal viral particles like human papillomavirus.

352
00:20:47.572 --> 00:20:50.612
Look at the pictures on the top. Those green are the ecDNA.

353
00:20:50.852 --> 00:20:53.912
Notice how they're taking a hitchhike onto chromosomes.

354
00:20:54.012 --> 00:20:56.912
Do ecDNAs look like this? Work back from Jeff Wahl's

355
00:20:57.932 --> 00:21:01.412
lab back in 2000 shows a pattern that looks remarkably

356
00:21:01.452 --> 00:21:04.382
similar. But how on earth does this actually work?

357
00:21:04.912 --> 00:21:08.552
So for episomal viruses, you have viral DNA

358
00:21:08.612 --> 00:21:12.272
elements that interact with viral proteins that interact with specific

359
00:21:12.312 --> 00:21:15.792
regions of the chromosome, and in work that was spearheaded by

360
00:21:15.852 --> 00:21:19.032
Venkat Sankar and King Hung,

361
00:21:20.232 --> 00:21:22.892
both graduate students in Howard's lab, Venkat is now in mine,

362
00:21:24.472 --> 00:21:26.832
and we basically went to look at this.

363
00:21:26.921 --> 00:21:29.012
And they developed a really clever idea.

364
00:21:29.552 --> 00:21:33.512
Chop up genomic DNA, put it into plasmids, and see what sticks

365
00:21:33.572 --> 00:21:35.132
around as retention elements.

366
00:21:36.481 --> 00:21:40.042
And you can see here, you get profiles like this that show when you encode certain

367
00:21:40.172 --> 00:21:43.112
sequences, the plasmids stick around.

368
00:21:43.732 --> 00:21:47.612
So what's on them? Well, it turns out they're loaded with promoters,

369
00:21:48.252 --> 00:21:50.492
and they're CpG-rich elements.

370
00:21:53.272 --> 00:21:56.062
And it gets even more interesting. They're additive.

371
00:21:56.522 --> 00:22:00.412
So you can imagine it like in this schematic on the right, two is better than one,

372
00:22:00.452 --> 00:22:03.392
three is better than two, four is better than three.

373
00:22:03.412 --> 00:22:05.051
And there's lots of these elements.

374
00:22:05.092 --> 00:22:09.072
So you can begin to imagine a physical basis for how this might

375
00:22:09.152 --> 00:22:12.612
actually work. So then we went to human cancers

376
00:22:12.952 --> 00:22:15.212
from public databases like the TCGA.

377
00:22:15.261 --> 00:22:18.852
And lo and behold, you have these retention elements very close to

378
00:22:18.892 --> 00:22:22.672
oncogenes. In fact, whenever you have an oncogene containing ecDNA, you

379
00:22:22.832 --> 00:22:26.732
have these retention elements. What they're doing is they're keeping them sticking

380
00:22:26.792 --> 00:22:30.632
around. And in fact, they have to be hypomethylated.

381
00:22:30.692 --> 00:22:34.612
You can see here that their signatures are those of hypomethylation, and

382
00:22:34.632 --> 00:22:38.082
when you experimentally methylate those regions,

383
00:22:38.612 --> 00:22:40.932
they no longer work as retention elements.

384
00:22:41.662 --> 00:22:44.312
So that raises yet another really interesting question.

385
00:22:44.981 --> 00:22:48.912
That suggests that there might be a protein machinery that's sitting in between.

386
00:22:49.292 --> 00:22:52.171
So we decided to look at that, or at least pieces of that.

387
00:22:52.192 --> 00:22:53.532
And I just want to state one

388
00:22:54.551 --> 00:22:58.192
fact that people haven't thought that much about, which is mitotic bookmarking.

389
00:22:58.572 --> 00:23:02.332
There's regions on chromosomes that have to stay open so that they're ready to

390
00:23:02.372 --> 00:23:06.112
go right after mitosis. These are called bookmarked regions, and

391
00:23:06.172 --> 00:23:10.012
it's pioneering transcription factors and chromatin remodelers that do that

392
00:23:10.072 --> 00:23:13.572
job. And Katarina Kraft did a

393
00:23:13.672 --> 00:23:17.252
mitotic Hi-C on this. And lo and behold, what we see is that

394
00:23:17.292 --> 00:23:21.282
promoter regions on the ecDNA are physically talking

395
00:23:21.412 --> 00:23:21.992
to

396
00:23:23.692 --> 00:23:27.522
bookmarked enhancer regions that are loaded with transcription factor

397
00:23:27.612 --> 00:23:31.112
binding sites on the chromosome. So now you're beginning to get a sense

398
00:23:31.532 --> 00:23:35.192
of how this might actually work. This is machinery that normally is

399
00:23:35.332 --> 00:23:39.062
used to regulate gene transcription and regulation,

400
00:23:39.552 --> 00:23:42.712
but the ecDNAs have pirated it to use that.

401
00:23:42.772 --> 00:23:45.912
And that actually suggests that looking at the

402
00:23:45.922 --> 00:23:49.532
proteins that are involved in that process might be a very fertile

403
00:23:49.542 --> 00:23:53.472
area for thinking about ecDNA-directed therapies.

404
00:23:53.552 --> 00:23:56.612
Just to point out one other thing about this, which is that

405
00:23:57.532 --> 00:24:01.432
it doesn't conflict with random segregation, because what you end

406
00:24:01.472 --> 00:24:05.292
up having here, imagine Disneyland when the buses go and there's a free-for-all

407
00:24:05.372 --> 00:24:09.312
running for the seats. It's exactly the same sort of a process.

408
00:24:11.412 --> 00:24:15.302
And just to finish, I'm going to go to a few important clinical

409
00:24:15.302 --> 00:24:19.112
points. Jens Lubec, sitting in the audience, and Vineet Bafna and I and other

410
00:24:19.172 --> 00:24:22.892
colleagues tried to ask what this means, particularly thinking about this issue

411
00:24:22.932 --> 00:24:26.052
about truncal versus branch and when does it happen?

412
00:24:26.392 --> 00:24:30.152
So we went to two pre-cancers. We went to people with Barrett's esophagus who are

413
00:24:30.172 --> 00:24:33.952
at risk of getting cancer. And in two studies, one that was led by

414
00:24:33.992 --> 00:24:37.772
Rebecca Fitzgerald at Cambridge, a study that was a snapshot

415
00:24:37.892 --> 00:24:41.472
study, and one that was led by Patty Gallipo and Tom

416
00:24:41.512 --> 00:24:44.584
Paulson at the Fred Hutch, where they looked at...

417
00:24:44.624 --> 00:24:48.604
tumor samples or tissue samples over space and time

418
00:24:48.684 --> 00:24:50.784
from those with Barrett's who did or did not get cancer.

419
00:24:51.144 --> 00:24:54.164
What we were really able to see was that in fact,

420
00:24:54.784 --> 00:24:58.544
ecDNA arose during high-grade dysplasia, always in the

421
00:24:58.584 --> 00:25:02.524
context of p53. And if it arose, those people would go on to

422
00:25:02.564 --> 00:25:06.494
get esophageal adenocarcinoma. That has really big implications because it

423
00:25:06.524 --> 00:25:09.674
means we need to look across other cancers or other

424
00:25:09.724 --> 00:25:13.514
pre-cancers to see ecDNA, because if it's there, it's

425
00:25:13.544 --> 00:25:15.464
likely to be a huge problem for these patients.

426
00:25:15.914 --> 00:25:19.794
So working with Maryam Jamal Hanjani, Charlie Swanton, and

427
00:25:19.884 --> 00:25:23.644
others in a study that was spearheaded by Chris Bailey and Oriol Pich, we looked at

428
00:25:23.684 --> 00:25:26.604
the Genomic England's data set to ask how common is

429
00:25:26.664 --> 00:25:29.624
ecDNA and in what cancer types, and what does it mean?

430
00:25:30.004 --> 00:25:33.884
So looking at close to 15,000 cancer samples of

431
00:25:33.904 --> 00:25:37.044
39 different types, we've seen that in at least

432
00:25:37.084 --> 00:25:40.824
17.1% of all cancers, the ecDNA or

433
00:25:41.084 --> 00:25:44.404
that the amplifications arose as ecDNA.

434
00:25:44.464 --> 00:25:48.424
We don't know if they're still there, but we know for certain that they arose as

435
00:25:48.464 --> 00:25:51.484
these circular ecDNA particles. And

436
00:25:52.484 --> 00:25:55.844
this is biased because these are largely earlier phase tumors.

437
00:25:56.024 --> 00:25:59.444
But you can see here huge spectrums bearing different

438
00:25:59.544 --> 00:26:03.224
cargos suggesting that tissue context is dramatically

439
00:26:03.304 --> 00:26:07.284
shaping the landscape of ecDNA. And in fact, they

440
00:26:07.304 --> 00:26:10.574
contain oncogenes, they contain immunomodulatory genes,

441
00:26:11.424 --> 00:26:14.584
they contain regulatory elements in all various combinations.

442
00:26:14.924 --> 00:26:18.884
And in fact, when they have the immunomodulatory genes, they have reduced T

443
00:26:18.984 --> 00:26:22.524
cell fractions. Most importantly, the patients who have

444
00:26:22.624 --> 00:26:26.424
ecDNA in their tumors do worse than all other cancer patients.

445
00:26:26.644 --> 00:26:30.424
These people are different, and that's why we need to be paying so much

446
00:26:30.464 --> 00:26:32.904
attention to them and what we can do about it.

447
00:26:34.144 --> 00:26:37.264
We are continuing to push the envelope of this biology.

448
00:26:38.464 --> 00:26:42.204
I'm just pointing out a study that we've done with our colleague, Anton

449
00:26:42.264 --> 00:26:45.824
Henson. He's going to be chairing a major session tomorrow on

450
00:26:45.844 --> 00:26:49.524
ecDNA biology, trying to understand what actually happens when the

451
00:26:49.644 --> 00:26:53.534
elements, the ecDNAs can't tether to the chromosomes,

452
00:26:53.684 --> 00:26:55.824
and what are the consequences of that.

453
00:26:55.864 --> 00:26:59.704
And also, I think I've mentioned this issue of the innate immune system

454
00:26:59.744 --> 00:27:00.804
and ecDNA.

455
00:27:02.624 --> 00:27:02.864
So

456
00:27:04.204 --> 00:27:08.124
this conversation started with ecDNA 12 years

457
00:27:08.184 --> 00:27:11.504
ago when only about three people in the world were actually interested in the

458
00:27:11.564 --> 00:27:14.644
topic. And it's culminated yesterday in the

459
00:27:14.704 --> 00:27:18.304
publication of an article in

460
00:27:18.364 --> 00:27:21.814
the anniversary issue of "The Hallmarks of Cancer," pointing

461
00:27:21.924 --> 00:27:25.644
out that ecDNA really is a critical

462
00:27:25.724 --> 00:27:29.684
enabler of the hallmark of cancer in those patients in whom that actually

463
00:27:29.724 --> 00:27:33.004
happens. This field has to move forward quickly.

464
00:27:33.104 --> 00:27:35.464
The patients need it. The door is open.

465
00:27:35.604 --> 00:27:38.934
We look forward to collaborating with you, and I am grateful to my

466
00:27:38.964 --> 00:27:42.904
colleagues. In particular, the Cancer Grand Challenges program has allowed

467
00:27:42.944 --> 00:27:45.224
us to work in a completely different way.

468
00:27:45.344 --> 00:27:49.284
I hope the data that I've shown you speaks to the power of that model, the

469
00:27:49.364 --> 00:27:53.104
people in my lab, the people in many other labs, and our ability to work

470
00:27:53.144 --> 00:27:55.304
together. And at that point, I'll say thank you.

471
00:28:01.684 --> 00:28:05.664
So I think we have time for a couple of questions, and then we can

472
00:28:05.684 --> 00:28:06.784
move on to the next talk.

473
00:28:11.804 --> 00:28:14.944
I just wonder what is the soft belly

474
00:28:15.804 --> 00:28:18.544
of extra chromosomal

475
00:28:19.784 --> 00:28:23.464
DNA? So this is relevant for two issues.

476
00:28:24.124 --> 00:28:25.804
First, why normal cells

477
00:28:27.084 --> 00:28:30.164
don't have, except maybe lymphocytes during development, don't have extra

478
00:28:30.204 --> 00:28:33.464
