00:42:56.968 --> 00:43:00.908
which orientation, and moreover, there might be high multiplicities of

723
00:43:00.988 --> 00:43:04.628
these segments in the genome. And so if you start extracting

724
00:43:04.648 --> 00:43:08.568
cycles from this graph, you can get many possible structures,

725
00:43:08.708 --> 00:43:12.408
and some combination of them form the true

726
00:43:12.448 --> 00:43:16.008
ecDNA repertoire. So it's definitely a problem that one would like

727
00:43:16.068 --> 00:43:19.968
to investigate further. With long reads and

728
00:43:20.008 --> 00:43:23.748
with some principle of using some kind of an Occam's razor

729
00:43:23.788 --> 00:43:27.568
saying maybe there are a few cycles that dominate, we might be

730
00:43:27.588 --> 00:43:29.808
able to disambiguate some of these structures.

731
00:43:29.848 --> 00:43:33.808
So in this particular case, we have so many species, but if you

732
00:43:33.868 --> 00:43:35.288
have some long reads that,

733
00:43:36.268 --> 00:43:39.908
for example, a long read that supports going from the

734
00:43:39.968 --> 00:43:43.928
segment B to the segment A to C, it can quickly

735
00:43:44.328 --> 00:43:48.288
disambiguate and say perhaps the structure on the right is the

736
00:43:48.348 --> 00:43:52.308
correct structure. And the way we think about these problems is

737
00:43:52.348 --> 00:43:56.338
to then say, can we explain the entire copy number of

738
00:43:56.408 --> 00:44:00.308
this amplicon using only a small number of

739
00:44:00.348 --> 00:44:04.158
cycles, which together explain all the structural variants,

740
00:44:04.628 --> 00:44:08.428
but also these different sub constraints that these long reads provide us?

741
00:44:08.648 --> 00:44:11.918
And it's sort of a challenging optimization

742
00:44:12.008 --> 00:44:15.868
problem. And when we solve it, we end up with very interesting structures.

743
00:44:16.008 --> 00:44:19.788
We have validated, of course, through simulations, but now we are looking at

744
00:44:19.848 --> 00:44:23.508
some complex structures and trying to see if the actual

745
00:44:23.628 --> 00:44:25.868
sequence that we predict makes sense.

746
00:44:25.998 --> 00:44:27.928
And so I'll give you a couple of examples.

747
00:44:27.968 --> 00:44:31.728
These are all well-regarded cell lines that people in the

748
00:44:31.768 --> 00:44:35.608
community use. Polo3.20 exists

749
00:44:35.708 --> 00:44:39.668
as an ecDNA, and when we analyze this, it turns

750
00:44:39.708 --> 00:44:43.128
out to have a very complex structure, almost over

751
00:44:43.328 --> 00:44:47.188
4.5 million base pairs long. When we look at it with our long

752
00:44:47.268 --> 00:44:50.968
read tools, we find that there are two cycles, and in fact, our

753
00:44:51.008 --> 00:44:54.668
recent data suggests that there might even be a one mega cycle of

754
00:44:54.928 --> 00:44:58.848
8 million base pairs. And so now the question is,

755
00:44:58.888 --> 00:45:02.608
do we believe these cycles? We are sort of picking at it

756
00:45:03.588 --> 00:45:07.548
point by point, but there are certain structural features that increase

757
00:45:07.588 --> 00:45:11.568
our confidence. One of them is that in this cycle, you can see

758
00:45:11.648 --> 00:45:15.208
that the PBT1 actually has a rearrangement that puts it

759
00:45:15.268 --> 00:45:18.628
upstream of the oncogene MYC, and that's a key

760
00:45:18.688 --> 00:45:21.508
rearrangement that's actually required for the

761
00:45:22.348 --> 00:45:25.688
MYC to be actually active and have high

762
00:45:25.728 --> 00:45:29.488
transcription. And so this increases our confidence that we have the

763
00:45:29.548 --> 00:45:30.908
right structures.

764
00:45:32.728 --> 00:45:36.048
We also looked at another cell line that has been studied quite a lot in the

765
00:45:36.088 --> 00:45:40.028
community, PC3DM. Surprisingly, there are not many published

766
00:45:40.088 --> 00:45:44.008
reports of its true structure. And when we look at it, the

767
00:45:44.048 --> 00:45:47.908
structure looks also very complicated, almost 4.5 million

768
00:45:47.968 --> 00:45:49.478
base pairs. And

769
00:45:50.628 --> 00:45:53.608
you can see many genes are repeated multiple times,

770
00:45:54.448 --> 00:45:58.348
something that it would be hard to sort of pick at and figure

771
00:45:58.408 --> 00:46:00.148
out whether it's a true structure or not.

772
00:46:00.178 --> 00:46:02.928
And we cannot say, of course, that it's entirely correct.

773
00:46:02.968 --> 00:46:04.008
But again,

774
00:46:04.928 --> 00:46:08.868
working with King Hung who graduated from Howard Chang's

775
00:46:08.908 --> 00:46:11.348
lab, we did this CRISPR-Cas experiment.

776
00:46:11.388 --> 00:46:15.308
So we take some guide RNA, and we cut at different locations where the

777
00:46:15.388 --> 00:46:18.508
guide matches, and that should give certain fragments.

778
00:46:18.548 --> 00:46:22.348
In this case, if our structure was correct, it would give you three

779
00:46:22.388 --> 00:46:26.008
fragments, two of which would be in excess of 1.5 million base

780
00:46:26.068 --> 00:46:29.888
pairs. And you can see in this gel that only with this

781
00:46:29.928 --> 00:46:33.208
guide RNA and with no other, you see exactly these fragments.

782
00:46:33.258 --> 00:46:34.908
So that increases our confidence.

783
00:46:35.468 --> 00:46:39.348
Then we also looked at some of the genes that co-occur on this and

784
00:46:39.388 --> 00:46:42.428
did a multi-FISH experiment with Ivy Wong.

785
00:46:43.088 --> 00:46:45.588
And you can see very nicely that these three

786
00:46:46.568 --> 00:46:50.468
oncogenes MYC, SAMD1/2, and FER1L6 all

787
00:46:50.548 --> 00:46:53.948
actually co-occur as

788
00:46:53.988 --> 00:46:57.808
ecDNA, again, increasing our confidence that this is a true structure.

789
00:46:57.908 --> 00:47:01.228
So the claim being that with long reads and with newer

790
00:47:01.268 --> 00:47:04.448
data, we are better able to analyze and

791
00:47:04.668 --> 00:47:08.548
reconstruct the true sequence of ecDNA. All right.

792
00:47:10.008 --> 00:47:13.768
So finally, in the small time that I have, we are

793
00:47:13.788 --> 00:47:17.268
also looking at chromatin capture data to see if we can

794
00:47:17.328 --> 00:47:21.168
understand the three-dimensional structure of ecDNA.

795
00:47:21.788 --> 00:47:24.448
And I won't have time to go into the algorithms.

796
00:47:24.608 --> 00:47:27.208
You can definitely look at the paper.

797
00:47:27.828 --> 00:47:31.048
It turns out that ecDNA have a very interesting and complex

798
00:47:31.468 --> 00:47:35.328
three-dimensional structure, not mediated solely by

799
00:47:35.338 --> 00:47:38.908
polymer physics, but actually by the transcription factors and the other

800
00:47:38.948 --> 00:47:42.148
proteins that might bind and change them.

801
00:47:42.228 --> 00:47:42.478
And

802
00:47:43.528 --> 00:47:45.468
we learned many things about them.

803
00:47:45.488 --> 00:47:49.288
For example, it wasn't known if the ecDNA would have a disk-like

804
00:47:49.328 --> 00:47:53.308
configuration or occupy the entire three-dimensional volume, and our results

805
00:47:53.318 --> 00:47:56.928
suggest that they do occupy this three-dimensional volume.

806
00:47:57.828 --> 00:48:01.548
We also did some orthogonal validation using high-resolution

807
00:48:01.608 --> 00:48:04.028
microscopy in a collaboration with

808
00:48:04.848 --> 00:48:08.728
Guy Nir's lab, and we can see very high correlation, even though

809
00:48:08.768 --> 00:48:12.598
both of these methodologies are not to a resolution where you can

810
00:48:12.628 --> 00:48:16.408
get down to get the exact structure, but the high correlation from these

811
00:48:16.468 --> 00:48:19.168
independent methods also increase our confidence.

812
00:48:19.928 --> 00:48:20.768
So how can we

813
00:48:22.168 --> 00:48:26.128
study and see if these structures actually

814
00:48:26.608 --> 00:48:29.868
can help us? Well, one thing is that they do a better job of

